Part II - Business Investments

by Sara Glattstein

Investigation Overview

Imagine there is a business you would like to provide financial support for. According to them, all you need to do it take a little bit of time to invest a little bit of money into their loan. You would like to believe that their business will be successful; despite this, it is important to remain realistic. Statistically, will the process of investing actually be as painless as they make it out to be?

Dataset Overview and Executive Summary

This dataset contains loan information collected by Prosper and made available through Udacity. More in depth information about it can be found here: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1gDyi_L4UvIrLTEC6Wri5nbaMmkGmLQBk-Yx3z0XDEtI/edit?gid=0#gid=0

The key insights I will be discussing are centered around business loans, their investor information, and the amount of time that the loan ultimately took to be paid off.

In[11]:
# load in the dataset into a pandas dataframe
df = pd.read_csv("./loan_dataset_final.csv")
df_concluded = df[(df['LoanStatus'] == 'Completed') | (df['LoanStatus'] == 'Chargedoff')]
df_completed = df[(df['LoanStatus'] == 'Completed')]
df_bus_comp = df_completed[(df_completed['LoanCategory'] == 'Business')]
df_bus_con = df_concluded[(df_concluded['LoanCategory'] == 'Business')]

Visualization 1

To start off, business loans have the greatest distribution of investors compared to loans taken out for other purposes.

In[6]:
#Creating a bivariate boxplot of Investors to LoanCategory
plt.figure(figsize = [10,6])
sns.boxplot(data=df_concluded, x='Investors', y='LoanCategory');
plt.xlabel('Number of Investors');
plt.ylabel('Loan Category');
plt.title('Investor Distribution Across Loan Categories');

This could be due to a variety of different factors, from the financial stability of the borrower to how successful their business has already been.

Visualization 2

It is easy to assume that loans with more investors behind them are more likely to proceed without difficulty.

In[21]:
#Making a multivariate scatterplot with color encodings
plt.figure(figsize = [10,6])
plt.scatter(data=df_bus_comp, x='LoanOriginalAmount', y='Investors', c='TimeDelta', cmap='icefire', alpha=1/2);
plt.xlabel('Loan Amount');
plt.ylabel('Number of Investors');
plt.colorbar(label='TimeDelta (months)');
plt.title('Timeliness of Completed Business Loans');

However, looking at the actual amount of time taken on completed loans shows that loans with more investors supporting them are often the ones that go beyond their term.

Visualization 3

It would also be inaccurate to assume that loans taken out by those with higher incomes are completely free of issue.

In[16]:
#Separating the data by range of income
IncomeIndex = ['Not employed', '$0', '$1-24,999', '$25,000-49,999',
               '$50,000-74,999', '$75,000-99,999', '$100,000+']

for group in IncomeIndex:
    #Selecting the subset of concluded loans
    group_data = df_bus_con[(df_bus_con['IncomeRange'] == group)]
    #Creating encodings for completed or charged off loan statuses
    ttype_markers = [['Completed', 'o'],['Chargedoff', '^']]
    plt.figure(figsize = [8,5])
    for ttype, marker in ttype_markers:
        plot_data = group_data.loc[group_data['LoanStatus']==ttype]
        #Creating the plot within these subsets for Loan Amount versus Investors
        sns.regplot(data=plot_data, x='LoanOriginalAmount', y='Investors', fit_reg=False, marker=marker, x_jitter=1000);


    #Setting the specific title for each subplot
    plt.suptitle(group, va='top')
    #Ensuring that each have a key to distinguish the resulting loan status
    plt.legend(['Completed', 'Chargedoff'])

Visualization 4

At the end of this investigation, the key takeaway is that there will always be some amount of risk associated with supporting a business. This is not to say that one should avoid investing their money or time into something they care about. Instead, it can serve as a reminder to really stop and consider the trajectory of your financial involvement. While it might seem simple at first to provide support, it very likely may end up turning into a process that spans years.

In[19]:
#Creating a bivariate heatmap comparing LoanAmount and TimeDelta
bins_x = np.arange(500, 30000, 2000)
bins_y = np.arange(-60, 60, 10)

plt.figure(figsize = [10,6])
h2d = plt.hist2d(data=df_bus_comp, x='LoanOriginalAmount', y='TimeDelta', cmap='viridis_r', cmin=0.3, bins=[bins_x,bins_y]);

counts = h2d[0]

# Add text annotation on each cell
# Loop through the cell counts and add text annotations for each
for i in range(counts.shape[0]):
    for j in range(counts.shape[1]):
        c = counts[i,j]
        if c >= 195: # increase visibility on darker cells
            plt.text(bins_x[i]+1000, bins_y[j]+5, int(c),
                     ha = 'center', va = 'center', color = 'white')
        elif c > 0:
            plt.text(bins_x[i]+1000, bins_y[j]+5, int(c),
                     ha = 'center', va = 'center', color = 'black')
            

plt.colorbar(label='Count');
plt.xlabel('Loan Amount');
plt.ylabel('TimeDelta (months)');
plt.title('Actual Duration of Loans by Their Amounts');
